38
00:01:51,542 --> 00:01:57,587
What you need to do before you start searching.

39
00:01:57,587 --> 00:02:02,671
A prototype is just about the most valuable thing you can have.

40
00:02:02,671 --> 00:02:05,433
Since I'm assuming you don't have an artist at this point,

41
00:02:05,433 --> 00:02:07,674
don't worry about making it look pretty.

42
00:02:07,674 --> 00:02:13,679
Just use Game Jam rules, grey box, asset store stuff,

43
00:02:13,679 --> 00:02:15,280
royalty-free assets, that's all good.

44
00:02:16,449 --> 00:02:20,430
You'll also need an idea about the work you want done,

45
00:02:20,430 --> 00:02:23,051
because that's gonna dictate the type of artist

46
00:02:23,051 --> 00:02:24,472
you need to look for.

47
00:02:24,472 --> 00:02:28,333
You know, a concept artist to help shape the vision,

48
00:02:28,333 --> 00:02:30,594
or a modeler to model characters and props,

49
00:02:30,594 --> 00:02:33,955
or a painter, or an animator, art director, et cetera.

50
00:02:33,955 --> 00:02:39,017
Now, this maybe seems like a, yeah, no shit kind of point,

51
00:02:39,017 --> 00:02:39,558
but it's...

52
00:02:40,418 --> 00:02:42,899
It's actually a pretty fine point.

53
00:02:42,899 --> 00:02:45,260
When Chickadee started working with Spryfox,

54
00:02:45,260 --> 00:02:49,281
it was because we answered a help wanted ad that said,

55
00:02:49,281 --> 00:02:52,022
hey, we need a modeler for our next project

56
00:02:52,022 --> 00:02:53,423
and bonus points if you can animate.

57
00:02:53,423 --> 00:02:56,424
But what they actually needed.

58
00:02:57,124 --> 00:03:02,366
was someone comfortable moving through the visual development process,

59
00:03:02,366 --> 00:03:06,768
someone who could do concept art, who could plan pipelines, who could do VFX,

60
00:03:06,768 --> 00:03:08,788
who could do a whole bunch of stuff.

61
00:03:08,788 --> 00:03:13,810
It was their first 3D project, and they sort of yet didn't know what they didn't know.

62
00:03:14,970 --> 00:03:17,893
And so if you're thinking like,

63
00:03:17,893 --> 00:03:19,535
oh, I thought I knew what I wanted,

64
00:03:19,535 --> 00:03:20,656
but maybe I don't now,

65
00:03:20,656 --> 00:03:24,780
try searching for a generalist or just a game artist.

66
00:03:24,780 --> 00:03:26,022
That's gonna be someone who's comfortable

67
00:03:26,022 --> 00:03:26,762
wearing a lot of hats.

68
00:03:28,883 --> 00:03:31,505
Reference of other work is also good to have.

69
00:03:31,505 --> 00:03:35,067
Reference that hits close to the emotional mark

70
00:03:35,067 --> 00:03:37,229
or kind of like the vibe you're going for.

71
00:03:37,229 --> 00:03:39,330
It's useful to have something to show,

72
00:03:39,330 --> 00:03:44,874
to get a potential artist in the same headspace as you.

73
00:03:44,874 --> 00:03:47,736
So go ahead and make a Pinterest board,

74
00:03:47,736 --> 00:03:49,177
just fill it up with stuff that,

75
00:03:49,177 --> 00:03:52,880
even if it's like, oh, this isn't the style of character

76
00:03:52,880 --> 00:03:53,801
we actually want.

77
00:03:54,381 --> 00:03:57,522
This, it feels right, right?

78
00:03:57,522 --> 00:04:00,002
It's okay to get emotional on that.

79
00:04:00,002 --> 00:04:02,222
Other media, this, kind of related to the last point,

80
00:04:02,222 --> 00:04:05,863
other media like music is sometimes really useful too,

81
00:04:05,863 --> 00:04:09,784
because it's useful to kind of sometimes make a,

82
00:04:09,784 --> 00:04:11,644
like a playlist and say,

83
00:04:11,644 --> 00:04:15,305
hey, this sounds the way the art should look, right?

84
00:04:15,305 --> 00:04:17,705
Get them in the same headspace as you.

85
00:04:17,705 --> 00:04:21,366
If you have, obviously, soundtrack samples or something,

86
00:04:21,366 --> 00:04:22,346
be ready to send those along.

87
00:04:22,346 --> 00:04:23,226
That's all good stuff.

88
00:04:23,667 --> 00:04:28,330
A list of verbs or adjectives is also good to have.

89
00:04:28,330 --> 00:04:31,332
Stuff that describe what the player should be feeling

90
00:04:31,332 --> 00:04:34,334
when they're playing the game or stuff,

91
00:04:34,334 --> 00:04:36,155
or what they should be thinking

92
00:04:36,155 --> 00:04:37,576
when they look at a screenshot.

93
00:04:37,576 --> 00:04:38,957
You know, I think verbs and adjectives,

94
00:04:38,957 --> 00:04:42,620
that's sort of like a common game design thing,

95
00:04:42,620 --> 00:04:44,281
but it's also really good for visual design.

96
00:04:44,281 --> 00:04:45,542
You know, and finally,

97
00:04:45,542 --> 00:04:47,643
you're gonna need a sense of your budget,

98
00:04:47,643 --> 00:04:48,864
and that is a big topic,

99
00:04:48,864 --> 00:04:51,786
so let's dive down into compensation, cha-ching!

100
00:04:53,268 --> 00:04:54,609
Come on, that was better.

101
00:04:54,609 --> 00:04:56,390
Give a little more.

102
00:04:56,390 --> 00:04:57,611
Okay, fine, I'll move on.

103
00:04:57,611 --> 00:04:59,392
Thank you, thank you, thank you.

104
00:04:59,392 --> 00:05:03,454
Okay, so the easiest, right, the most straightforward way

105
00:05:03,454 --> 00:05:06,336
is like to pay an artist is just to have an art budget,

106
00:05:06,336 --> 00:05:08,397
which is maybe not fair in an IGS talk.

107
00:05:08,397 --> 00:05:13,780
But right, like, hey, I need art, and here is the money,

108
00:05:13,780 --> 00:05:15,821
and then now I thank you for the art.

109
00:05:17,950 --> 00:05:20,892
But again, IGS talk, let's talk about other stuff.

110
00:05:20,892 --> 00:05:23,154
Royalties, profit sharing, that kind of stuff,

111
00:05:23,154 --> 00:05:24,035
that's also an option.

112
00:05:24,035 --> 00:05:27,677
Obviously that takes away the upfront burden of payment,

113
00:05:27,677 --> 00:05:29,458
or at least eases it.

114
00:05:29,458 --> 00:05:31,760
But it's something to consider.

115
00:05:31,760 --> 00:05:35,263
If you're offering royalties without having proof

116
00:05:35,263 --> 00:05:37,504
that you've successfully shipped a game,

117
00:05:37,504 --> 00:05:38,725
that's sort of gonna make...

118
00:05:39,185 --> 00:05:45,571
that in an appealing payment scheme because there's risk that that payment never comes.

119
00:05:45,571 --> 00:05:54,678
There's a few points in this whole talk where your work history or your reputation in the

120
00:05:54,678 --> 00:05:56,219
community, it's going to add a lot of weight.

121
00:05:56,219 --> 00:05:57,240
This is one of those points.

122
00:05:58,181 --> 00:06:01,544
uh... if people have good things to say about you or they have a positive

123
00:06:01,544 --> 00:06:02,565
impression

124
00:06:02,565 --> 00:06:04,767
of the past games you've made

125
00:06:04,767 --> 00:06:08,350
uh... that's going to take some that risk out of the prospect of royalties

126
00:06:08,350 --> 00:06:10,953
you know and and you shouldn't be afraid of

127
00:06:10,953 --> 00:06:12,674
of using that that's a tool in your tool kit

128
00:06:14,213 --> 00:06:15,814
Again though, if you're just maybe starting out,

129
00:06:15,814 --> 00:06:17,134
you don't have that reputation yet,

130
00:06:17,134 --> 00:06:20,815
you're still building up, still there's other options.

131
00:06:20,815 --> 00:06:23,235
You know, if you don't mind going with someone

132
00:06:23,235 --> 00:06:26,276
who has maybe less experience than you'd like,

133
00:06:26,276 --> 00:06:27,696
depending on the laws in your area,

134
00:06:27,696 --> 00:06:29,176
you might be able to get an intern for free

135
00:06:29,176 --> 00:06:31,436
so long as they're doing it through their university,

136
00:06:31,436 --> 00:06:32,917
they're getting credit.

137
00:06:32,917 --> 00:06:35,517
You know, they get experience, you get art,

138
00:06:35,517 --> 00:06:37,938
it probably will need to be touched up

139
00:06:37,938 --> 00:06:39,718
because again, they're just starting out,

140
00:06:39,718 --> 00:06:43,038
but you know, it gets the ball rolling, you have some art.

141
00:06:44,733 --> 00:06:48,034
Beyond that though, this is such an important point.

142
00:06:48,034 --> 00:06:52,235
Offering credit or experience or exposure

143
00:06:52,235 --> 00:06:54,836
is like flagrantly shitty.

144
00:06:54,836 --> 00:06:55,756
Just don't do it.

145
00:06:55,756 --> 00:07:00,777
Don't be afraid to get creative with payment.

146
00:07:00,777 --> 00:07:01,918
One option is working for trade.

147
00:07:01,918 --> 00:07:03,538
Now the obvious thing is like, oh hey,

148
00:07:04,413 --> 00:07:08,695
Maybe you both have side projects and like you trade code for art or something like that.

149
00:07:08,695 --> 00:07:10,355
But I think you can get more creative than that.

150
00:07:10,355 --> 00:07:13,916
I one time did, this is true, I one time did

151
00:07:13,916 --> 00:07:18,217
not a ton of work, but a good amount of work

152
00:07:18,217 --> 00:07:21,998
for a bunch of super delicious home-brewed beer.

153
00:07:21,998 --> 00:07:24,819
And I personally think I got the better deal

154
00:07:24,819 --> 00:07:28,780
because I got drunk for like many days and they just got some assets.

155
00:07:29,561 --> 00:07:30,402
But we were both happy.

156
00:07:30,402 --> 00:07:32,045
The point is that we were both happy

157
00:07:32,045 --> 00:07:33,046
with the arrangement, right?

158
00:07:33,046 --> 00:07:34,709
That's creative, we felt good.

159
00:07:34,709 --> 00:07:35,850
Especially me.

160
00:07:38,363 --> 00:07:43,046
So another option is to allow the artist to retain rights

161
00:07:43,046 --> 00:07:45,007
to the work they make.

162
00:07:45,007 --> 00:07:47,769
When I was starting out, I did a bunch of work

163
00:07:47,769 --> 00:07:50,951
for different studios with me retaining the rights

164
00:07:50,951 --> 00:07:52,452
to the assets I produced.

165
00:07:52,452 --> 00:07:54,673
And then after the game shipped or after the contract

166
00:07:54,673 --> 00:07:57,715
was over, I would package up some of that art

167
00:07:57,715 --> 00:07:59,877
and I would sell it in asset stores.

168
00:07:59,877 --> 00:08:03,119
And they got a lower cost or a lower price because of that.

169
00:08:03,399 --> 00:08:05,880
because I was able to make up the difference

170
00:08:05,880 --> 00:08:08,521
selling to third party markets, right?

171
00:08:08,521 --> 00:08:13,382
So let's talk briefly about experience

172
00:08:13,382 --> 00:08:15,342
as it relates to budget.

173
00:08:15,342 --> 00:08:19,084
An experienced artist, someone with a bunch of ship titles,

174
00:08:19,084 --> 00:08:22,365
they're gonna have a higher rate.

175
00:08:22,985 --> 00:08:25,807
than someone who's more junior, I think obviously.

176
00:08:25,807 --> 00:08:28,429
But their experience can ultimately save you money

177
00:08:28,429 --> 00:08:32,111
because they're not gonna be hitting,

178
00:08:32,111 --> 00:08:34,213
they'll be jumping over hurdles

179
00:08:34,213 --> 00:08:36,955
that someone more junior might hit.

180
00:08:36,955 --> 00:08:39,197
In that regard, they're sort of getting more done

181
00:08:39,197 --> 00:08:40,778
in less time.

182
00:08:40,778 --> 00:08:42,499
But going with someone more junior,

183
00:08:42,499 --> 00:08:43,560
it actually might be the start

184
00:08:43,560 --> 00:08:46,962
of a really long and fruitful relationship.

185
00:08:46,962 --> 00:08:48,564
Junior people are gonna cost less,

186
00:08:48,564 --> 00:08:51,286
they're gonna make more mistakes,

187
00:08:51,286 --> 00:08:51,786
but.

188
00:08:53,454 --> 00:08:55,536
Everybody gets better with time, right?

189
00:08:55,536 --> 00:08:57,838
So if you're talking to someone, they don't quite

190
00:08:57,838 --> 00:09:00,061
have the experience you wish they did, but you really get

191
00:09:00,061 --> 00:09:03,665
along with them on a personal level, consider putting that

192
00:09:03,665 --> 00:09:06,288
time in to help them grow.

193
00:09:06,288 --> 00:09:07,549
OK, let's keep moving.

194
00:09:09,003 --> 00:09:12,044
Where to search for your new artist?

195
00:09:12,044 --> 00:09:16,546
So first and maybe most obvious, your own network.

196
00:09:16,546 --> 00:09:17,867
People you've worked with in the past,

197
00:09:17,867 --> 00:09:21,489
people you've met at local meetups or stuff like this.

198
00:09:21,489 --> 00:09:28,332
These people are resources and you can mine that resource.

199
00:09:28,332 --> 00:09:30,453
It's sort of the whole point of a network, right?

200
00:09:32,640 --> 00:09:35,102
sort of related to that, recommendations, right,

201
00:09:35,102 --> 00:09:39,406
they're sort of actually my favorite way of finding people.

202
00:09:39,406 --> 00:09:41,627
You know, if a friend or a dev I respect

203
00:09:41,627 --> 00:09:44,029
is singing the praises of someone,

204
00:09:44,029 --> 00:09:48,433
they immediately get a million bonus de grande points

205
00:09:48,433 --> 00:09:52,456
when I'm weighing them against other people.

206
00:09:52,456 --> 00:09:55,918
This is another place where having good reputation,

207
00:09:55,918 --> 00:09:56,999
it can really help you out.

208
00:09:58,149 --> 00:10:02,435
If one of my favorite people is looking for someone,

209
00:10:02,435 --> 00:10:05,039
I'll excitedly scan my own network

210
00:10:05,039 --> 00:10:06,982
to see if I can find a matchup.

211
00:10:06,982 --> 00:10:10,286
Just the thought of these two people working together,

212
00:10:10,286 --> 00:10:12,109
it's like, oh, that's gonna be sweet.

